                        <condition>Handle text with caution. In fair condition with many detached
                           folios and historical repairs.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="16" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column with 16
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in a hasty
                           <material>black</material> shikastah-ta‘līq with <material>red</material>
                        subheaders.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions><lb/>
                     <label>Table of Contents:</label> The <locus from="vb" to="via">fifth right
                        flyleaf b side to sixth a side (f. vb–via)</locus> lists the contents of the volume.<lb/>
                     <label>Marginalia:</label> Occasional notes throughout in an unidentified
                     English hand written in sepia ink, which translates chapter headings and events
                     and cross-references Dow's translation.<lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions</label>: The <locus from="Inner_front_cover"
                        to="Inner_front_cover">right board exterior</locus> bears a paper label with
                     the French title and volume number and <q xml:lang="fr">Nº 58</q>, as well as
                     bears another note describing on the <locus from="iia" to="iia">second right
                        flyleaf a side (f. iia)</locus> both by former owner <persName
                        role="fmo ins seal" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/122375965"
                        key="person_122375965">Jean Baptiste Joseph Gentil (1726-1799)</persName>,
                     who also signed and <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>, top.<lb/> Folio <locus
                        from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears a note by former owner <persName
                        role="seal ins fmo">Yūsuf Muḥammad Khān</persName> dated <date
                        calendar="#Hijri-qamari">1149 AH</date> indicating that he paid a price of
                     140 rupees for the three-volume set:<lb/>
                     <q>له ملک هفدهم ۱۷ ماه مبارک رمضان سنه ۱۱۴۹ از خجسته بنایل(؟) سه جلد تاریخ
                        فرشته بقیمت سلع(؟) یکصد و چهل روپیه خرید شده در قلعه بر پیدا (؟) رسید
                        (سیاق؟) چند روزی بعاریت از ماست</q>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_front_cover"
                        to="Inner_front_cover">right</locus> and <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left</locus> doublures both bear Chetham's bookplates,
                     the latter with the class mark <q>7994</q>. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Probably uniformly rebound as a set in <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502" key="place_7001502"
                              >Awadh</placeName> for former owner <persName role="fmo"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/122375965" key="person_122375965">Jean
                              Baptiste Joseph Gentil (1726-1799)</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn at two unsupported stations, with straight-grained, medium-weight,
                           ivory-coloured, externally sized and polished endpapers, probably
                           handmade in <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502" key="place_7001502"
                              >Awadh</placeName> with ~7 laid lines per cm and no discerible chains
                           lines added at the beginning and end. Edges trimmed, with chevron
                           endbands twined in yellow and green silk over round cores at <locus
                              from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail"
                              >tail</locus>. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus> lined with
                           wide strips of paper adjacent to the sewing as false bands. Covered in
                           full maroon goatskin <material>leather</material>, tight-backed, over
                           pasteboards, flush-cut with the edges, but without a flap (Type III
                           binding per Déroche), with internal doublures of the same
                              <material>leather</material>, their excess widths adhered as hinges
                           connecting to the first and last flyleaves to the cover, with strips of
                           paper applied over top to disguise the joins.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Board margins ruled in wide white lines, doulble
                           ruled either side, with additional double and single ruling connecting
                           the corners and single vertical lines through through the centres. After
                           ruling, the binder decorated the boards with blind-stamped central
                           scalloped mandorlas, detached pendants, and angular cornerpieces. Blind
                           single palette lines by the false bands on the spine.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>284</height>
                              <width>181</width>
                              <depth>76</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle with extreme caution. Binding in poor condition, with
                           boards detached and textblock split in several areas. Remnants of the
                           false spine bands remain on the spine, endbands missing.
                           Boxed.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>Two black intaglio-carved seal impressions:</summary>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>1:</label> The <locus from="ia" to="ia">first right flyleaf a side
                              (f. ia)</locus> bears an partly legible black rectangular seal
                           impression, intaglio-carved in lines of nasta‘liq script, double-ruled,
                           with the names and titles of former owner <persName role="fmo ins seal"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/122375965" key="person_122375965">Jean
                              Baptiste Joseph Gentil (1726-1799)</persName> dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1768" to="1769">1182 (1768–1769
                              CE)</date>: <q xml:lang="fa">جنتیل بهادر ناظم جناب پذیر الملک رفیع
                              الدوله ۱۱۸۲ </q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>19</height>
                              <width>23</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="octagon">
                        <p><label>2:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears an
                           octagonal seal impression bearing the name of former owner or associate
                              <persName role="seal ins fmo">Yūsuf Muḥammad Khān</persName>, possibly
                           dated regnal year 12, which due to the adjacent inscription dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari">1149 AH</date>, would likely be that of the
                           Mughal ruler of Delhi <persName role="other" key="person_45680638"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/45680638">Muḥammad Shāh (b. 1702, r.
                              1819–1848)</persName>.<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>13</height>
                              <width>19</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Completed by an unidentified scribe in the <origPlace
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace> undated, but <origDate calendar="#Gregorian"
                        cert="medium" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1785">probably mid-18th century
                        CE</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently purchased by one <persName role="seal ins fmo">Yūsuf
                           Muḥammad Khān</persName>, as per his notation on folio <locus from="1a"
                           to="1a">1a</locus>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Later acquired by French military figure <persName
                           role="fmo ins seal" key="person_122375965"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/122375965/">Jean-Baptiste Gentil (1726–1799
                           CE)</persName>, as per his seal impression on the <locus from="iia"
                           to="iia">second right flyleaf a side (f. iia)</locus>. He fought the
                        British East India Company in Pondicherry, Bengal, and Awadh, the latter
                        fighting on behlaf of Shuja‘ al-Dawlah.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Gentil retired and returned to France in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1778">1778</date>, he offered his collection
                        for sale under the guise of the late <q xml:lang="fr">Chevalier de Caunun,
                           Ancien Gouverneur de Chandernagor</q> on <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1789-07-11">9 July 1789</date>, pp. 7–8, Nº LVIII.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>While the circumstances under which this volume arrived in Britain
                        remain unclear, <persName role="fmo" key="person_92189357">John Haddon
                           Hindley (1765–1827)</persName> subsequently acquired it and offered it
                        for sale through the <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134139493" key="person_134139493">Leigh and
                           Sotheby</persName> on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1793-03-10">10
                           Mar. 1793</date>, p. 43, no. 1264</p>.</provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Haddon thereafter apparently sold the set to <orgName role="rps"
                           key="person_155994771" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/155994771">Chetham's
                           Library</orgName>, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477" key="place_7010477"
                           >Manchester</placeName> while serving there as librarian, since the set
                        appears in Greswell's 1826 catalogue published the year before his
                        death.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Purchased in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1981">1981</date> by the
                           <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                        together with other oriental manuscripts for £2000.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
